## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK resolves dependencies **two ways**:

| Style | How it works |
|-------|-------------|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | The class is instantiated per-request; DI services go in the primary constructor. Use for `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, custom services. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services appear as method parameters alongside user-facing params. The SDK distinguishes them automatically — DI params are **never** exposed in the tool schema. |

**What's auto-injected (hidden from schema):**
- `CancellationToken` — cooperative cancellation
- `IMcpServer` — server instance for notifications
- `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` — progress reporting
- Any type registered in DI (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, your own services)

Only parameters decorated with `[Description]` appear in the tool's JSON schema that the LLM sees. This means you freely mix user inputs and infrastructure in the same method signature.
